\par 13 - Does your study involve children and/or young people (i.e. younger than 18 years)?
\par No
\par 15 - Does your study involve people in existing dependent or unequal relationships with the researcher(s)?
\par Yes
\par 30 - Existing dependent or unequal relationshipYou have indicated that an Existing dependent or unequal relationship would be included in your study. Please answer the following additional questionsDescribe the existing dependent or unequal relationship

\par For undergraduate psychology students who participate for course credit, the researchers involved may be teaching on or coordinating units of study that student participants are enrolled in.
\par 
\par However, the students are
 able to choose from a range of other studies, or to complete an alternative task in order to obtain course credit for research participation. There is no direct approach from the researchers, and so no coercion or perceived coercion to participate. Stude
nts will read study ads online (on the SONA system) and can sign up to any studies they choose.
\par 
\par 31 - How will the process of obtaining consent avoid perceived/actual coercion and enable persons in dependent relationships to give voluntary consent?(NB: after answering this question, you will be directed back to Section B)
\par Undergraduate psychology stud
ents can elect to participant in this study as one of many research studies on offer, and there is no direct approach from the researchers. The students anonymously sign up to participate in this study through the SONA system. The PIS also state that shou
ld the participant wish to withdraw from the study, there will be no adverse consequences on their relationship with the researchers or university.
\par 29 - Does your research involve people with a cognitive impairment, an intellectual disability or a mental illness?
\par Possible Recruitment
\par 33 - Does your research involve people highly dependent on medical care who may be unable to give consent?
