\par 215 - SECTION DThe questions in Section D are specifically directed at the consent process.Describe how you will identify and select potential participants for recruitment into
 the study. You should include information about how you will obtain contact details for potential participants.
\par 
\par 1) Sydney University Psychology Research (SONA) participant system. First year psychology (PSYC1001 and PSYC1002) complete SONA studies for course credit. 
\par 
\par 2) We will utilise the "paid" version of SONA (SONA_PAID) where students can complete studies for financial compensation. 
\par 
\par 2) Advertising on online crowdsourcing platforms (Prolific Academic/Amazon's Mturk)
\par 
\par 3) Participants from previous research studies who have consented to be contacted via email to be invited to participate in future research studies.
\par 
\par 4) Advertising on online social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.
\par 
\par 217 - Describe how and where initial contact will be made w
ith potential participants and how you will avoid real or perceived coercion. Copies of all relevant correspondence (e.g. email, letter of introduction, covering letter, circular/flyer etc.) need to be uploaded with your application. If you are using emai
l addresses please outline how their use will not be in breach of privacy or spam legislation.
\par 1) SONA system: We intend to recruit participants through the Sydney University Psychology Research (SONA) participant system, where first- and second-year psychology students sign up and participate in experiments in exchange for course credit. SONA oper
ates in accordance with the School of Psychology\rquote 
s guidelines on research participation. In addition, SONA has a paid version which we will also utilise, where students can participate in studies in exchange for nominal financial compensation. The advertisements for both are in the attached documents

\par 
\par 2) Prolific Academic/Amazon's Mturk: We will recruit participants via the two online crowdsourcing platforms Prolific (https://www.prolific.co) and Mturk (https://www.mturk.com). In both platforms, individuals 
can sign-up to online studies to complete in exchange for nominal financial compensation. The study advertisement will appear in the feed of individuals who have registered on these website. These individuals can choose to participate in this study (click
ing through to the PIS, consent form & online study on the study advertisement) or a wide range of other studies advertised on the website.
\par 
\par 3) Previous research participants who have consented to be contacted about future research studies will be contacted
 via the email addresses provided by these participants. These individuals will be invited to participate using the email template (see attached documents). Apart from this email, there will be no direct contact from the researchers. Those who wish to par
ticipate can then click on the URL provided within the email to access further information about the study, provide consent and complete the online study from their computer.
\par 
\par 4) For recruitment on social media, the online advertisement (see attached docume
nts) will be circulated on Facebook, Twitter, and other social media platforms. The flyer will contain a URL to the Participant Information Statement (PIS), consent page, and online study. There will be no direct contact with participants from the researc
hers.
\par 
\par 218 - If a participant, or person on behalf of a participant, chooses to withdraw from the research, what specific consequences should they be made aware of, prior to giving consent? These details should be included in the Participant Information Sta
tement.
\par If SONA psychology student participants withdraw from the study prior to completion, they will forgo their course credit. This is stated on the Participant Information Statement.
\par 
\par If participants recruited via the paid version of SONA or the online
 crowd sourcing platforms (Prolific and Mturk) withdraw from the study prior to completion, they will not receive the financial compensation and this is stated in the relevant Participant Information Statement.
\par 
\par 219 - Will participants receive any reimbursement of out-of-pocket expenses, or financial or other "rewards" as a result of participation?
\par Yes
\par 221 - Specify the nature and value of any proposed incentive/payment (e.g. movie tickets, food vouchers) or reimbursement (e.g. travel expenses) to participa
nts. Explain why this offer will not impair the voluntary nature of the consent, whether by participants or persons deciding for their behalf. Payment that is disproportionate to the time involved, or any other inducement that is likely to encourage parti
c
ipants to take risks, is ethically unacceptable. (See 2.2.10 and 2.2.11 of the National Statement). Note that monetary amounts should not be specified in advertisements, but payments should be disclosed in the Participant Information Statement in accordan
ce with 2.2.6 (j) of the National Statement.
\par SONA participants: First year psychology students will receive 1 hour of course credit point per hour of study (pro rata). It is stated in their handbook that research participation is voluntary, and they may ele
ct to do a written assignment as an alternative to research participation. The PIS also states that they are free to withdraw from the study at any time.
\par 
\par SONA_PAID participants: Participants recruited via SONA_PAID will be compensated at a rate of $10 AUD
 per hour. This payment is inline with the standard rate on the platform. Participants can select from a range of studies and the PIS also states that they are free to withdraw from the study at any time.
\par 
\par Online crowdsourcing participants: Participant on online crowdsourcing platforms (Prolific and Mturk) will be compensated at a rate of \'a3
6.00 (~$10.19 AUD) per hour. This payment is inline with the standard rate on the platform (e.g. https://www.prolific.co/pricing). Participants can select from a range of
 studies and the PIS also states that they are free to withdraw from the study at any time.
\par 
\par Participants recruited via social media will not receive financial compensation 
\par 
\par The studies in this protocol have a range of durations and the pay for a particular study will be calculated by multiplying the expected time by these hourly rates (e.g. a 30 minute study on Prolific will offer \'a33 compensation)
\par 
\par The monetary amounts are specified in all advertisements and Participant Information sheets and are in line with normal payment rates of the recruitment pathways
\par 
\par 220 - How will consent be obtained (more than one may apply)
\par Other
\par 222 - Please clarify your response to the question above and justify with reference to the National Statement (e.g. sections 2.2.5, 3.1.16, 5.2.16). For instance, if you indicated that consent will be written and oral, does this refer to all participants 
u
ndergoing written and oral consent or does it refer to different consent processes for different participant groups? You should also justify why you have chosen these forms of consent. If you are using oral consent, explain how it will be recorded (e.g. i
n field notes, using tape recording).
\par Consenting participants will provide digitally consent (attached) by selecting an appropriate checkbox on the computer. This is to ensure participants have read and understood the information provided in the PIS.
