\par 232 - SECTION EThe questions in Section E relate to how you will protect participants\'e2\'80\'99 p
rivacy and the confidentiality of their information in your research project. Will any part of the project involve recordings (e.g. audio, video, online surveys)?
\par Yes
\par 235 - Which of the following recordings will be used in the project? More than one may apply.
\par Online surveys
\par Other
\par 236 - Outline how these recordings will be used and why they are necessary to achieve the aims of the research project. If your project involves online surveys, state where the surveys will be hosted and comment on any security, d
ata ownership and privacy constraints associated with this survey host.
\par The responses to the online surveys and cognitive tasks will constitute the data that will be analysed to address the projects research aim. The surveys are administered using online p
latforms, including Qualtrics hosted by the School of Psychology, University of Sydney. Cognitive tasks are hosted online via html servers. All data storage and hosting locations are password protected and encrypted. No identifiable data is stored with su
rvey/cognitive task responses ensuring participant anonymity
\par 234 - Will you be collecting information/data about a participant from a third party (i.e. another individual)?  Please note that this DOES NOT include agencies or organisations.
\par No
\par 237 - The foll
owing questions will establish whether the HREC needs to apply federal or state/territory privacy legislation when reviewing your ethics application.Will you use, collect or disclose information about human participants from an agency, authority or organi
s
ation? This includes Commonwealth agencies, private sector organisations, state/territory agencies and international organisations. For instance, you may be using information from a medical practice, a hospital, a university, a state or federal government
 department. You should say \'e2\'80\'98yes\'e2\'80\'99 even if it is your own organisation (e.g. your medical practice). 
\par No
\par 241 - Is the research project likely to produce information or results that are of personal significance to individual participants? For instance, a 
project may reveal that participants are at risk of developing a particular disease, provide insight into their intellectual/other abilities, or indicate that they have physical or mental health problems.
\par No
