\par Psychiatric or clinical psychology studies, or  psychological experiments
\par 364 - Are you doing research in a context which requires you to get permission from an appropriate authority e.g. a school, corporation, NGO, or similar?
\par No
\par 365 - Outline in lay language the theoretical, e
mpirical and/or conceptual basis, background evidence for the research proposal with reference to the relevant literature (include at least four research citations).  Note, that your study should be "based on a thorough study of the current literature, as
 well as previous studies" (NS 1.1 c).
\par Educators have focused on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901 improving}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981  knowledge by targeting learners\rquote 
 metacognition, the higher-order skill of monitoring and controlling one\rquote s cognitive processes. However, metacognitive interventions are of
ten heavily reliant on the instructor providing hints or prodding students to draw on previous knowledge. As a result, students often struggle to use these interventions independently. Given the increasing use of online and self-directed learning, this is
 particularly problematic. One promising avenue to improve knowledge in a scalable and independent way is the use of metacognitive self-evaluation. 
\par 
\par Metacognitive self-evaluatio}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901 n occurs where one rates their performance or evaluates their cognitive process. This evaluation can be prompted through ratings and self-report scales (e.g. eliciting
 confidence ratings from participants). Studies suggest that prompting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901\charrsid11479981 metacognitive self-evaluation can}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901  sometimes}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901\charrsid11479981  improve reasoning performance on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901 cognitive tasks }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901\charrsid11479981 
(e.g., Double & Birney, 2017, 2018, 2019)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901 . However, the results are mixed and we need a better understanding of the moderators of the effect of metacognitive self-evaluation as well as the mec
hanisms that produce these effects. T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 his project will examine }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2387901 the moderators and mechanisms of the relationship between 
metacognitive self-evaluation and cognitive performance.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 
\par 
\par References
\par Double, K. S., & Birney, D. P. (2017). Are you sure about that? Eliciting confidence ratings may influence performance on Raven\rquote s progressive matrices. Thinking & Reasoning, 23(2), 190\endash 206.
\par Double, K. S., & Birney, D. P. (2018). Reactivity to confidence ratings in older individuals performing the latin square task. Metacognition and Learning, 13(3), 309\endash 326.
\par Double, K. S., & Birney, D. P. (2019). Do confidence ratings prime confidence? Psychonomic Bulletin & Review, 26(3), 1035\endash 1042.
\par 367 - Outline in lay language the methodology for the research proposal. Note, that you study should be "designed or developed using methods appropriate for achieving the aims of the proposal" (NS 1.1 b). Your response should include:\'e2\'80\'a2\tab 
Aims and  hypotheses/research questions\'e2\'80\'a2\tab Research plan including duration of the study and/or timeline\'e2\'80\'a2\tab Participant characteristics including sex, age range and inclusion/exclusion criteria (if relevant)\'e2\'80\'a2\tab 
The intended sample size with a justification, and/or the particiant sampling/selection strategy (as relevant to your study)\'e2\'80\'a2\tab Details of where the study will be undertaken (location/site/URL)\'e2\'80\'a2\tab 
Details of how data will be collected and analysed\'e2\'80\'a2\tab Potential significance of the study
\par Aims and hypotheses/research questions
\par 
\par The goal in these studies is to examine the effect of metacognitive self-evaluation on cognitive performance and the pathways by which it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 ffects cognitive performance. To address this goal there are two major aims:
\par Aim 1: to explore how the characteris
tics of metacognitive self-evaluation prompts interact with the learning environment (task and judgement characteristics) to impact cognitive performance. To understand the potential of metacognitive self-evaluations, these studies will adopt an experimen
tal perspective to understand how prompts should be worded, as well as when and in what context they should be administered to facilitate cognitive performance. 
\par 
\par Aim 2: to investigate how participant characteristics moderate the effect of metacognitive self-evaluation on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 cognitive performance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 . Studies under this aim will examine how individual differences in participant characteristics (e.g., self-efficacy, metacognitive efficiency, cognitive ability, and goal orientations) moderate the effects of metacogniti
ve self-evaluation on cognitive performance. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2518241 Studies addressing these aims will be run iteratively, to develop an empirical framework of how, when, and for whom metacognitive self-evaluation affects cognitive performance.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2518241\charrsid11479981 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 
\par Research plan including duration of the study and/or timeline
\par 
\par Studies will be run from 2022-202}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 
\par 
\par Aim 1
\par The research will start with the experimental studies needed to address Aim 1. To achieve this aim, a series of experiments will be run examining the effect of different metacognitive self-evaluation prompts (e.g., \lquote 
How confident are you that you answered the last item correctly?\rquote 
) on cognitive performance on a range of traditional cognitive tasks. These experiments will compare evaluation vs no evaluation conditions. The metacognitive prompts will have different wording, ratings scales etc. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 
\par To ensure that the effect of metacognitive self-evaluation is generalisable and robust we will utilise a range of typical cognitive tasks. T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 
he tasks used in these experiments capture a broad range of cognitive abilities. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13334039\charrsid11479981 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 The cognitive tasks will include:
\par Cognitive Tasks: The cognitive tasks include: the Relation Monitoring Task, Task switching, AX-CPT task, Change Detection, Raven\rquote s Advanced Progressive Matrices, Letter Series, Latin Square Task, Spatial-Relation Task, Stroop, Anti-sacc
ade, Choice Reaction Time, Simple Span (Letter, Digit), and Complex-Span (Operation), N-back, Flanker Task, perceptual discrimination tasks, categorisation tasks. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7887464 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 Details of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 the cognitive tasks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981  
are provided in the attached }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 Appendix \endash  Cognitive Tasks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981  document.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7408022 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 Aim 2
\par Subsequent studies will introduce individual differences measures to address Aim 2. These studies will examine how person-level characteristics moderate the effect of metacognitive self-evaluation. 
\par The individual differences measures will include:
\par 
\par Surveys: Big-5 personality, Self-efficacy, implicit theories of intelligence, Need for Cognition, cognitive reflection task, Goal Orientations, emotional intelligence, Narcissism 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7887464 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 Details of each survey and participant characteristics questions are provided in the attached }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 Appendix - }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7887464\charrsid11479981 Survey Specification document.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7408022 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid8274416 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8274416\charrsid11479981 
The precise combination of cognitive tsks and surveys included in each study will be iteratively determined in order to develop an increasingly robust theory of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8274416\charrsid11479981 how metacognitive 
self-evaluation affects cognitive }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid606948\charrsid11479981 performance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8274416\charrsid11479981 
 from each experiment, while informing the design of each study with those
 that proceeded it. We anticipate each study will range from 15 minutes to 60 minutes in length. Each study will be extensively piloted to accurately estimate completion time. Participant will be compensated at the rates outlined in Q221 of the ethics for
m. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7408022 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8274416\charrsid11479981 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7408022\charrsid11479981 Participant characteristics including sex, age range and inclusion/exclusion criteria (if relevant), ratings of English competency
\par 
\par The studies will be open to participants from English speaking countries (Australia, UK, US, etc.) and over the age of 18 years old.
\par 
\par The intended sample size with a justification, and/or the participant sampling/selection strategy
\par 
\par Sample sizes will differ for each study based on the number of conditions, measures etc. For each study, the sample size will be based on a priori power analyses using 80% power with small-to-medium effect size estimates.
\par 
\par 
\par Details of where the study will be undertaken (location/site/URL)
\par 
\par 
\par The study will be completed online. Surveys will be hosted on Qualtrics (https://www.qualtrics.com/) and cognitive tasks will be hosted on Australian-based USYD servers and linked to/from Qualtrics 
\par 
\par 
\par Details of how data will be collected and analysed
\par 
\par Data will be collected online. We will principally use multilevel modelling to explore the interaction between experimental condition and person factors, along with traditional univariate statistics (ANOVA, t-test)
\par 
\par 
\par Potential significance of the study 
\par 
\par The project will provide an evidence-based understanding of how me
tacognitive self-evaluation affects cognitive performance. There is an ever increasing need to transfer skills and knowledge between domains. In addition, the complexity and global nature of many of today\rquote 
s problems necessitates increasing flexible skills 
and interdisciplinary knowledge. To facilitate cognitive performance in a meaningful way we need an approach that can be applied in a self-directed manner throughout a lifetime of learning. Metacognitive evaluations can be generalised to almost any subjec
t
 or domain, and they do not require additional information or resources from an external party (e.g., a teacher). Therefore, researching and developing metacognitive self-evaluations has huge potential to improve educational outcomes in a cost effective a
nd scalable way. 
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkend Questionnaire}
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16384045 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10303296\charrsid11479981 
